Robert Lunte Review: The Four Pillars of Singing




Rex





					February 23, 2017				



How to Learn Singing / Reviews 


Tweet
Program: The Four Pillars of Singing
Product Type: Singing Program
Company: The Vocalist Studio
Founder: Robert Lunte
Price: From $97
My Rating: 9 out of 10
 

 
The Four Pillars of Singing – Product Overview
There are many singing programs on the Internet, and one of my favorite(which is very few) is Robert Lunte’s The Four Pillars of Singing. You have to understand that I come from the Mix school of singing, something that is very different from, or even opposite of , Robert Lunte’s method. More than a year ago, I decided to try something different to see what coaches from other singing schools have to say about singing, so I decided to join Robert’s program for one year. Boy, was I impressed!
1. One of the Most Complete Singing Program Online
If you simply visit Robert Lunte’s website of The Vocalist Studio, you’d be impressed with what you see there. You will see different packages of singing training with combinations of the online training program The Four Pillars of Singing, the hard copy and ebook of the program, and private singing lessons with Robert himself. In order not to get overwhelmed by everything that’s offered on the website, let’s just focus on the entry package of THE online course and system The Four Pillars of Singing.
2. 167+ High-Def Training Videos – Lectures & Training Routines


Since I had joined this singing program for a year, I can give you an inside look and my user experience with The Four Pillars of Singing. Basically, it’s a website with more than 167 high-quality training videos that you can watch and practice singing with. Robert is very professional with his video production, and since he’s always demonstrating when he’s teaching in the videos, the sound quality is superb (I’m involved in music production at work, so I can assure you). It’s very comfortable watching those videos with Robert explaining his singing method. Since we’re not interested with just watching videos, I can tell you that the most important thing, which is the content is very comprehensive and easy-to-follow, without losing depth and sophisticated details, when you train with the videos.

The videos are catergorized into several sections, starting with lectures on singing myths and the TVS methodology, explaining each onset trainings that help to build vocal coordination and muscular strengths. Then, it has an extensive video section on training routines(a lot of them) in which Robert walks you through all the exercises (He sings them with you, and that’s where you’ll hear and see him hitting high Cs and above in full voice). Basically, the coordination training gets you to balance out the registers and get good tone quality in your voice, and the strength-building training works out your vocal muscle to get your voice stronger and higher.
3. The Four Pillars of Singing – The Book and Ebook
The program also comes with a book, also called The Four Pillars of Singing, which is a 600-page book that fully explains his method and training routines. But if you want to get the book, it cost a lot more than just joining the website($197). For me, the training website is already good enough for me, which only cost $97 for one year of access. I paid $197 for the ebook and the website because that was the entry package offer back then.

 
Robert Lunte – the Vocal Coach and the Method

While I don’t 100% agree or follow his method, I have to say that Robert is a master of vocal pedagogy. His knowledge of singing technique is not only vast and complete, he also has a gift of breaking down very complicated concepts of singing pedagogy into simple terms that anyone can understand. I was introduced by Robert the concept of onsets(how you start a sound), and its importance in vocal training through his videos. He uses 8 different onsets to train singers for vocal coordination and strength building- each serves a different purpose.
He is one of the few vocal coaches(if not, the only) from the belt school that trains bridging and connecting, because usually the teacher is either one or the other – belt(bottom-up) or bridge and connect(top-down), he does a superb job in combining these two most important aspect of singing in his methodology, which is very rare because teachers from both schools don’t like or agree with each other. In the end, the students get all the benefits.

 
Live Chat with Robert Himself

When you visit his website, there is a little window on the bottom right that says “live chat,” which means Robert is around to talk with you, or “leave a question” when he’s not around. That little window was where I got acquainted with Robert personally. He is very responsive with chats and questions – he answered almost everytime I asked a question! Although I discontinued my membership due to busy personal schedule(I started grad school and work full-time at the same time), he still answers my emails whenever I write to him.


Conclusion
If my personal singing technique was not so deeply rooted in Mix, I would choose Robert’s singing system The Four Pillars of Singing to train myself, because it’s just so complete and deals with almost every aspect of singing. I’m just very impressed with the system he has built. It’s not easy to come up with your own system, and Robert did it. I was very skeptical before joining since I don’t like it when a teacher is trying to be original with an ancient art. But I must say, as an experienced and advanced singer, I was very impressed(did I say that already?) with his system after joining – Robert is not inventing something new- he’s systemizing it in a new and innovative way that anyone in the modern world could learn and benefit from his singing system.
If you have any questions or comments, please leave a message, and I’ll be happy to discuss with you.
 





